The paper focuses on the development of a low-cost, vision-based teleoperation system for a dexterous robotic hand-arm system. This involves the use of computer vision techniques to track and interpret the movements of a human hand, which is then used to control the robotic system. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.RO (Robotics), which deals with the design, control, and operation of robots. 

The paper also involves the use of computer vision techniques, such as hand tracking and gesture recognition, which fall under the category of cs.CV (Computer Vision). Additionally, the system is designed to learn sensorimotor policies for challenging manipulation tasks, which involves the use of machine learning techniques, falling under the categories of cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) and cs.LG (Machine Learning). 

Finally, the paper also involves human-robot interaction, as the system is designed to enable operators to carry out a variety of complex manipulation tasks. This falls under the category of cs.HC (Human-Computer Interaction).
